        2,
        "**Subject-Verb Agreement** requires that a singular subject takes a singular verb and a plural subject takes a plural verb. The SAT makes this challenging by separating the subject and verb with long phrases designed to distract you from the true subject.\n\n"
        "**The Core Rule**\n\n"
        "- Singular subject: 'The dog **runs** in the yard.'\n"
        "- Plural subject: 'The dogs **run** in the yard.'\n\n"
        "Note the paradox: singular verbs in the present tense typically end in -s ('runs', 'is', 'has'), while plural subjects take verbs without -s ('run', 'are', 'have').\n\n"
        "**Finding the True Subject: Cross Out Prepositional Phrases**\n\n"
        "A prepositional phrase begins with a preposition (of, in, with, by, between, among, for, to, etc.) and ends before the verb. The noun inside a prepositional phrase is never the subject.\n\n"
        "Strategy: cross out the prepositional phrase, then check agreement.\n"
        "- 'The box [of apples] **is** on the counter.' (Subject = box, singular)\n"
        "- 'The impact [of the new policies] **is** still being studied.' (Subject = impact, singular)\n\n"
        "**Tricky Case 1: Collective Nouns**\n\n"
        "Words like **team, committee, class, family, government, jury, board** are treated as **singular** in American English because they act as a single unit.\n"
        "- 'The committee **has** reached its decision.'\n"
        "- 'The jury **was** unable to reach a verdict.'\n\n"
        "**Tricky Case 2: Indefinite Pronouns (Always Singular)**\n\n"
        "The following pronouns are always singular, no matter what follows them: **each, every, either, neither, one, nobody, everyone, everybody, someone, somebody, anyone, anybody, no one.**\n"
        "- 'Each of the students **is** responsible for submitting a report.'\n"
        "- 'Everyone in the two departments **agrees** on the deadline.'\n\n"
        "**Tricky Case 3: Or/Nor -- Agree with the Closer Subject**\n\n"
        "When subjects are joined by **or** or **nor**, the verb agrees with the subject closest to it.\n"
        "- 'Neither the manager nor the employees **were** informed.' (closer = employees, plural)\n"
        "- 'Neither the employees nor the manager **was** informed.' (closer = manager, singular)\n\n"
        "**Tricky Case 4: Inverted Sentences (There is/are...)**\n\n"
        "In sentences beginning with 'There' or 'Here', the true subject comes after the verb. Find the real subject first, then choose the verb.\n"
        "- 'There **are** three options on the table.' (subject = options, plural)\n"
        "- 'There **is** a single flaw in the design.' (subject = flaw, singular)\n\n"
        "**Before / After Correction Examples**\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The box of antique tools are stored in the basement.' -- Correct: '...is stored...'\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The committee have voted to delay the decision.' -- Correct: '...has voted...'\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Each of the proposals were reviewed thoroughly.' -- Correct: '...was reviewed...'\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Either the CEO or the board members was notified.' -- Correct: '...were notified...' (closer = members)\n\n"
        "**Full SAT-Style Question**\n\n"
        "Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard Written English?\n\n"
        "The collection of ancient scrolls discovered in the desert caves ______ now displayed in a temperature-controlled gallery at the national museum.\n\n"
        "(A) are\n"
        "(B) were\n"
        "(C) is\n"
        "(D) have been\n\n"
        "**Answer: (C)**\n\n"
        "- **(A) 'are'** -- Incorrect. 'Are' is a plural verb, but the subject 'collection' is singular.\n"
        "- **(B) 'were'** -- Incorrect. 'Were' is plural past tense; the context ('now displayed') requires a present tense singular verb.\n"
        "- **(C) 'is'** -- Correct. 'Collection' is the singular subject. Cross out 'of ancient scrolls discovered in the desert caves' (prepositional and participial modifiers). 'Collection...is now displayed' -- singular subject, singular verb, present tense.\n"
        "- **(D) 'have been'** -- Incorrect. 'Have been' is a plural present perfect form. It does not agree with the singular subject 'collection'.\n\n"
        "⚠️ **Common Mistake:** Agreeing the verb with the noun inside a prepositional phrase (like 'scrolls') rather than with the true subject ('collection'). The SAT places long phrases between subject and verb precisely to trigger this error.\n\n"
        "💡 **Tip:** Cross out every prepositional phrase between the subject and verb before you check agreement. This single habit eliminates the most frequent subject-verb agreement traps on the SAT."
