        3,
        "**Pronoun Agreement** requires that a pronoun match its antecedent in number and gender. **Pronoun Case** requires using the correct form of the pronoun based on its grammatical role. Both skills are tested frequently on the SAT.\n\n"
        "**Agreement: Match the Antecedent**\n\n"
        "The antecedent is the noun a pronoun replaces. Every pronoun must agree with its antecedent in number (singular/plural).\n"
        "- Singular antecedent: 'The company revised **its** policy.'\n"
        "- Plural antecedent: 'The companies revised **their** policies.'\n\n"
        "**Indefinite Pronoun Antecedents**\n\n"
        "Indefinite pronouns (each, everyone, anyone, someone, nobody, either, neither) are always singular, so the pronoun referring back to them must also be singular.\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Each student submitted their essay.' (In formally edited prose, use singular: 'his or her essay.')\n"
        "- Correct: 'Each student submitted his or her essay.'\n\n"
        "**Ambiguous Reference**\n\n"
        "A pronoun is ambiguous when it could logically refer to more than one noun. Fix ambiguity by replacing the pronoun with the specific noun.\n"
        "- Ambiguous: 'When Maria told Sofia the news, she burst into tears.' (Who is 'she'?)\n"
        "- Clear: 'When Maria told Sofia the news, Sofia burst into tears.'\n\n"
        "**Subject Pronouns vs. Object Pronouns**\n\n"
        "- **Subject pronouns** (used as the subject of a verb): I, he, she, we, they, who\n"
        "- **Object pronouns** (used as object of verb or preposition): me, him, her, us, them, whom\n\n"
        "Test: remove the companion noun to isolate the pronoun.\n"
        "- 'The award was given to my lab partner and ___.' Remove 'my lab partner and': 'The award was given to me.' Never 'to I.'\n\n"
        "**Who vs. Whom: The He/Him Substitution Test**\n\n"
        "Rearrange the clause and substitute:\n"
        "- If **he/she** fits naturally → use **who**\n"
        "- If **him/her** fits naturally → use **whom**\n\n"
        "- 'She is the scientist **who** discovered the compound.' (She discovered -- 'she' fits → use 'who.')\n"
        "- 'He is the scientist **whom** the committee honored.' (The committee honored him -- 'him' fits → use 'whom.')\n\n"
        "**Reflexive Pronouns (myself, himself, herself, themselves)**\n\n"
        "Use reflexive pronouns only when the subject and object of the verb refer to the same person.\n"
        "- Correct: 'She hurt herself.' (same person -- subject and object identical)\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The award was presented to my partner and myself.' (Use 'me,' not 'myself.' The subject of the sentence is not the same as the object.)\n"
        "Never use 'myself' as a substitute for 'me' just because it sounds more formal.\n\n"
        "**Before / After Correction Examples**\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Between you and I, the deadline is unrealistic.' -- Correct: 'Between you and **me**...' (object of preposition 'between')\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Everyone on the team must complete their own report.' -- Correct: '...must complete **his or her** own report.'\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Please send the documents to whoever is in charge.' -- Correct: 'Please send the documents to **whoever** is in charge.' (Subject of the clause 'is in charge' → subject form 'whoever')\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The coach spoke to the player who the team had elected.' -- Correct: '...the player **whom** the team had elected.' (team elected him → 'whom')\n\n"
        "**Full SAT-Style Question**\n\n"
        "Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard Written English?\n\n"
        "The scholarship was awarded to ______ the faculty committee judged to have the strongest academic record.\n\n"
        "(A) whoever\n"
        "(B) whomever\n"
        "(C) who\n"
        "(D) whom\n\n"
        "**Answer: (B)**\n\n"
        "- **(A) 'whoever'** -- Incorrect. 'Whoever' is a subject-form pronoun. But within the clause 'the faculty committee judged ___ to have the strongest record,' the pronoun is the object of 'judged' (the committee judged him/her). Object form is needed.\n"
        "- **(B) 'whomever'** -- Correct. The pronoun is the object of both 'to' and of 'judged' within the embedded clause. Substitute: 'the committee judged him' -- 'him' fits, so object form. Because the entire clause is the object of 'to', use 'whomever.'\n"
        "- **(C) 'who'** -- Incorrect. Subject form; incorrect when the pronoun functions as an object.\n"
        "- **(D) 'whom'** -- Incorrect in this context. 'Whom' works as a simple object pronoun in a non-embedded clause. Here, the pronoun heads an entire noun clause, requiring 'whomever.'\n\n"
        "⚠️ **Common Mistake:** Using 'I' after a preposition because it sounds formal or educated. Prepositions always take object pronouns: 'with me,' 'between us,' 'for him,' 'to her.'\n\n"
        "💡 **Tip:** To test who vs. whom (or whoever vs. whomever), rearrange the clause and substitute he or him. If 'he' works, use 'who/whoever'; if 'him' works, use 'whom/whomever.'"
