        5,
        "**Parallel Structure** (also called parallelism) requires that items in a series, list, or comparison share the same grammatical form. When items in a list are not parallel, the sentence feels inconsistent and violates standard written English.\n\n"
        "**The Core Rule**\n\n"
        "All items in a series must be the same part of speech or the same verb form.\n\n"
        "- Incorrect (mixed forms): 'She likes hiking, to swim, and running on the beach.'\n"
        "- Correct (all gerunds): 'She likes **hiking, swimming, and running** on the beach.'\n"
        "- Correct (all infinitives): 'She likes **to hike, to swim, and to run** on the beach.'\n\n"
        "**Parallelism in Comparisons**\n\n"
        "When comparing two things, both sides of the comparison must use the same grammatical structure. Avoid comparing an action to a noun or a gerund to an infinitive.\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The cost of renting is higher than to buy.' (gerund vs. infinitive)\n"
        "- Correct: 'The cost of **renting** is higher than the cost of **buying**.'\n\n"
        "**Correlative Conjunctions -- All Pairs Require Parallelism**\n\n"
        "Correlative conjunctions come in fixed pairs. The grammatical structure after the first word of the pair must match the structure after the second word.\n\n"
        "| Pair | Rule |\n"
        "| not only...but also | noun/noun or verb/verb |\n"
        "| either...or | matching forms on each side |\n"
        "| neither...nor | matching forms on each side |\n"
        "| both...and | matching forms on each side |\n"
        "| whether...or | matching forms on each side |\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The report was **not only** thorough **but also** it was convincing.'\n"
        "- Correct: 'The report was **not only** thorough **but also** convincing.' (both adjectives)\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'She will **either** accept the position **or** she will negotiate the terms.'\n"
        "- Correct: 'She will **either** accept the position **or** negotiate the terms.' (both bare verbs)\n\n"
        "**Parallelism in Series of Clauses**\n\n"
        "When a sentence contains multiple clauses, each clause should have the same structure.\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The committee agreed to review the evidence, holding new hearings, and a final report would be issued.'\n"
        "- Correct: 'The committee agreed to **review** the evidence, **hold** new hearings, and **issue** a final report.' (all bare infinitives)\n\n"
        "**Before / After Correction Examples**\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'The program is designed to increase enrollment, retain students, and the improvement of outcomes.'\n"
        "  Correct: '...to increase enrollment, retain students, and improve outcomes.' (all bare infinitives)\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Running five miles is as challenging as to lift heavy weights for an hour.'\n"
        "  Correct: 'Running five miles is as challenging as lifting heavy weights for an hour.'\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'She is both a talented singer and writes poetry beautifully.'\n"
        "  Correct: 'She is both a talented singer and a gifted poet.'\n\n"
        "- Incorrect: 'Whether you study tonight or there is relaxation -- it is your choice.'\n"
        "  Correct: 'Whether you study tonight or relax -- the choice is yours.'\n\n"
        "**Full SAT-Style Question**\n\n"
        "Which choice completes the text so that it conforms to the conventions of Standard Written English?\n\n"
        "The new city budget aims to expand public parks, modernize transit systems, and ______.\n\n"
        "(A) the improvement of local schools\n"
        "(B) improving local schools\n"
        "(C) local schools will be improved\n"
        "(D) improve local schools\n\n"
        "**Answer: (D)**\n\n"
        "- **(A) 'the improvement of local schools'** -- Incorrect. A noun phrase; the first two items ('expand,' 'modernize') are bare infinitives. The third must also be a bare infinitive.\n"
        "- **(B) 'improving local schools'** -- Incorrect. A gerund phrase; this does not match the bare infinitive form of 'expand' and 'modernize.'\n"
        "- **(C) 'local schools will be improved'** -- Incorrect. A full independent clause; this breaks the list structure entirely and creates a run-on or grammatical mismatch.\n"
        "- **(D) 'improve local schools'** -- Correct. A bare infinitive that matches 'expand' and 'modernize,' creating a grammatically parallel list.\n\n"
        "⚠️ **Common Mistake:** Mixing gerunds and infinitives in the same list without noticing the shift. 'Hiking, to swim, and running' may sound acceptable in speech, but it violates parallelism in formal writing.\n\n"
        "💡 **Tip:** Underline each item in the series and label its part of speech or verb form. If the labels differ, the sentence lacks parallelism and needs a fix."
